## AI is throwing app developers into a [roiling sea of constant market chaos.](https://x.com/yishan/status/2011002996663243152) This article suggests new business models that will emerge from the destruction.

The space to grow a new app business is squeezed. Big foundation model vendors are squeezing from the top by releasing AI which does a lot of the things that a dedicated app will do. The normal way to compete with a big company is to find markets that are too small for them, but roomy for a startup. However, it is more difficult to grow in a small market when customers and pop-up competitors use AI to generate alternatives and squeeze you from the bottom.

Adding to the pressure, the whole concept of an app is shrinking. User interfaces are irrelevant if our preferred UI is "talk to an AI". The AI uses tools to deliver the result that we want, and it can generate a UI on the fly. This accelerates new tool adoption because an AI can use a tool before we put any specific UI or workflow around it. It also cuts value out of existing full-featured apps. That is why SaaS stocks fell off a cliff about the time that stock analysts started trying Claude Code.

### **Getting out of the squeeze**

AI will give us explosive new business models, but they will be different business models.

New app developers are squeezed from the top and bottom. The new business models need to push back on both ends of the squeeze.

* They need to work at a scale that matches large foundation model vendors  
* They need to outrun and recruit smaller startups and customers

Let's look at four different ways to make an app.

## **Commercial software production**

Commercial software is produced by vendors, who send it to users. This is a powerful business model that covers a huge range of applications. It has problems when customers and AI are outrunning the vendor.

## **Open Source software production**

Open Source software reverses the flow of code. Users send in modifications, and the "maintainer" merges them. Power users are motivated contribute, because they get back a high quality release that includes their feature, with a promise to maintain it and extend it in the future.

![Article content][image4]

Open Source software works where you have motivated contributors and maintainers. Open Source software runs the internet and other critical infrastructure. Open Source works as a way to handle AI generated code, except when the load on the maintainer becomes enormous.

## **User \+ AI software production**

In the age of AI, everyone is a potential contributor. The AI takes prompts and turns them into code and skills. We can ask the AI to contribute the prompts (showing the use case or "intent"), and the generated code and skills.

![Article content][image5]

This is a bit different from the open source workflow because we can see the prompt and the use case that goes with the code. It's also different because we are getting machine generated slop. It is being generated at high volume, with many overlapping versions of the same use case. It needs to be cleaned up or rebuilt before we can put it in a distribution.

We will want a merge process that looks at the incoming prompts and code, finds the most common and most useful cases, and builds higher quality versions to put in a release. We will want to automate this process. The automation might use a lot of computation, resulting in what I will call "code mining".

The open source process runs into problems when maintainers cannot keep up. Code mining turns this into an advantage. It thrives on an active user base submitting a flood of use cases. It outruns the squeeze with sheer velocity.

## **AI sourcing with commercial enhancements**

Code mining needs to run at the speed of AI, and a scale that matches what the foundation model vendors are doing. This will cost some money. It gives us a motivation to add some commercial economics.

### **Revenue**

Many users of open source will pay for a distribution that is tested for a higher level of quality and stability than the version that maintainers and power users will build for themselves. That adds subscription revenue.

### **Funding**

AI is a big money game. We need a mechanism to fund the initial ramp to subscription quality. TIPL or "Tokenized IP License" can pay for the tools and compute that go into code mining, and can reward contributors.

Tokenized IP License (TIPL) starts with a crypto token. It adds value to a token by adding a buyout right. An acquirer that makes a successful tender offer for the token gets control of the related IP (while preserving open source rights). A TIPL can cover a wide variety of IP, including data, branding, social content, internal tools, and the resulting apps. We can easily distribute these tokens to contributors. Follow TIPL in [this repository](https://github.com/MaxosLLC/TIPL).

I am proposing this new mechanism in order to:

* Start quickly. TIPL can drop onto emerging AI-sourced projects without additional structuring. It does not require a company. It can even be launched by an AI.  
* Harness the most common driver of startup value, which is the future value of a buyout.  
* Engage all of the contributors

People have good reasons to be skeptical of crypto projects. They often feature memes and "narratives", sell tokens, and extract trading revenue. TIPL is not that. It is a simple tool for organizing a project that includes a lot of contributors from different places.

We are proposing two new mechanisms \- code mining, and TIPL. If this works, we can instantly support emerging applications with code mining workflow and drop-in licensing. Functionality should ramp up quickly from that point.
